[On 10 Aug 2018, China submitted to the OIE its 2nd ASF follow-up report, informing absence of new outbreaks since the initial report, submitted on 3 Aug 2018. In the 1st report, the start of the event was given as 1 Aug 2018.

The 2nd follow-up report included the following commentary:
"After all susceptible animals at the infected point and infected zone were culled and disposed of in an appropriate bio-safety way, the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs has organized and guided veterinary services of the whole country to conduct an epidemiological survey and emergency surveillance for African swine fever (ASF). Up to 9 Aug 2018, a total of 261 900 screening sites were investigated and a total of 18 094 300 pigs were screened in our country. Sites included pig farms, markets, slaughterhouses, factories, or sites for disposal of animals and animal products. Epidemiological survey and emergency surveillance plan has been issued by the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs. In the key provinces including Beijing, Tianjin, Hebei, Inner Mongolia, Liaoning, Jilin, Heilongjiang, Guangdong, Gansu, Xinjiang, Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps, an epidemiological survey and emergency surveillance for ASF have been conducted according to the plan. Up to now, no new cases have been found."

From the current paper it appears that the event had started, in fact, the latest in mid-June 2018; the virus might have been spreading undetected since. The efforts invested in the investigation and the transparency reflected by the current publication, are impressive. The Chinese authorities have a huge, globally unprecedented undertaking on their hands to try prevent the spread of the disease throughout a subcontinent which harbours about half of the world's domestic pig population. This becomes even more complex in view of the need to address also ASF vectors -- wild boar and ticks.

As the authors rightly indicate, the need for an effective ASF vaccine has become vividly crucial. - Mod.AS

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of China: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5967476,29090]
